&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s create a fake flag file:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Jakarta</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-jakarta/</link><pubDate>Wed, 04 Nov 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-jakarta/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta.jpg"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta.jpg"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There&amp;rsquo;s a manual:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta-dets.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta-dets.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Passwords that are &lt;strong&gt;too long are rejected&lt;/strong&gt;. There is additional mechanisms to &lt;strong&gt;verify password length&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The lock is &lt;strong&gt;attached to&lt;/strong&gt; LockIT Pro &lt;strong&gt;HSM-1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta-hsm1.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta-hsm1.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; function just calls &lt;code&gt;login&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;login&lt;/code&gt; function is quite long:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta-input-dets.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta-input-dets.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta-login-2.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta-login-2.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta-login-3.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jakarta/jakarta-login-3.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Authentication requires a username and password input. The prompt states that these inputs together may &lt;strong&gt;not be more than 32 characters&lt;/strong&gt;. :D&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Santa Cruz</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-cruz/</link><pubDate>Wed, 04 Nov 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-cruz/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cruz/cruz.jpg"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cruz/cruz.jpg"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Nice! Here is a lock. This is the manual:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cruz/santa-details.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cruz/santa-details.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Passwords that are &lt;strong&gt;too long are rejected&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is not much clues from the manual.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; function just calls the &lt;code&gt;login&lt;/code&gt; function:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cruz/santa-login.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cruz/santa-login.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Authentication requires a username and password input. The prompt states that these inputs should be between 8 and 16 chars. :D&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bytes &lt;code&gt;0x0, 0x8 and 0x10&lt;/code&gt; are set into the addresses at &lt;code&gt;r4 - (0x6, 0x19,0x18)&lt;/code&gt; respectively. This will probably make sense soon.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Novosibirsk</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-novo/</link><pubDate>Tue, 03 Nov 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-novo/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/novo/novo.jpg"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/novo/novo.jpg"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;but a manual:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/novo/nov-dets.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/novo/nov-dets.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The lock is &lt;strong&gt;attached to LockIT Pro HSM-2.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Features have been added from the &lt;strong&gt;b.03&lt;/strong&gt; to the hardware.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Passwords &lt;strong&gt;can not be too long.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So this hardware version differs from &lt;em&gt;b.03&lt;/em&gt; in that HSM-2 is what is connected to port 2.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/novo/novo-hsm2.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/novo/novo-hsm2.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Also, &lt;em&gt;passwords cannot be too long&lt;/em&gt;. Mmmh?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; function:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/novo/nov-login.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/novo/nov-login.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The input buffer for username:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Addis Ababa</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-addis/</link><pubDate>Tue, 01 Sep 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-addis/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/addis/addis.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/addis/addis.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You get to Addis Ababa and find a lock with a manual:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/addis/addis-dets.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/addis/addis-dets.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The lock is &lt;strong&gt;attached to HSM-1 module&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Passwords &lt;strong&gt;cannot be too long&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Usernames are &lt;strong&gt;printed back&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Flag &lt;strong&gt;set in memory&lt;/strong&gt; if password is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Usernames are printed back&lt;/em&gt;. This must be a clue. You think of &lt;strong&gt;format string&lt;/strong&gt; vulnerabilities. Note to self: &lt;code&gt;Printf&lt;/code&gt;!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is the &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; function:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/addis/addis-main.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/addis/addis-main.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;r14&lt;/code&gt;: the length of the input buffer is &lt;code&gt;#0x13(19)&lt;/code&gt; characters.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;r15&lt;/code&gt;: the input buffer is at address &lt;code&gt;0x2400&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The input is copied to another destination at address &lt;code&gt;0x3a34&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The input is then passed to &lt;code&gt;test_password_valid&lt;/code&gt;; a flag is set depending on whether the password is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The copied input is then printed back using &lt;code&gt;printf&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;tst 0x0(sp)&lt;/code&gt; checks if flag is set before call to &lt;code&gt;unlock_door&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A quick run with test input: &lt;code&gt;aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa&lt;/code&gt; (19 characters) to study program flow.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Johannesburg</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-jo/</link><pubDate>Tue, 01 Sep 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-jo/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jo/jo.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jo/jo.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At this point in the journey, you expect a manual to greet you:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jo/jo-details.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jo/jo-details.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The lock is &lt;strong&gt;attached to HSM-1 module&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Passwords that are &lt;strong&gt;very long are rejected&lt;/strong&gt;. Just how long is too long?&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; function just calls &lt;code&gt;login&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jo/jo-login.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/jo/jo-login.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The prompt states the password range should be within &lt;code&gt;8 - 16&lt;/code&gt; characters long. However, from the input parameters of the &lt;code&gt;getsn&lt;/code&gt; function:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Montevideo</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-monte/</link><pubDate>Tue, 01 Sep 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-monte/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/montevideo/monte.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/montevideo/monte.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You find a manual:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/montevideo/monte-dets.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/montevideo/monte-dets.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;This lock is &lt;strong&gt;attached to HSM-2 module&lt;/strong&gt;. This means, no unlock door function in the lock firmware. This reminds you of a while back in &lt;a href="https://evalevanto.github.io/blog/microcorruption-whitehorse"target="_blank"&gt;&lt;em&gt;WhiteHorse&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The code follows &lt;strong&gt;internal secure development process&lt;/strong&gt;. mmh.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; function just calls &lt;code&gt;login&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/montevideo/monte-login.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/montevideo/monte-login.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The prompt states for an input range of &lt;code&gt;8 - 16&lt;/code&gt; characters. However, from the input to &lt;code&gt;getsn&lt;/code&gt; function:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Reykjavik</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-reykjavik/</link><pubDate>Tue, 01 Sep 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-reykjavik/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/reykjavik/reykjavik.jpg"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/reykjavik/reykjavik.jpg"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Military-grade security lock they say. Here is the manual:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/reykjavik/reykjavik-details.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/reykjavik/reykjavik-details.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;This lock is &lt;strong&gt;not attached to any HSM module&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Military-grade &lt;strong&gt;on-device encryption&lt;/strong&gt; has been implemented to keep the password secure.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Passwords entered &lt;strong&gt;cannot be read from memory&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is the &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; function:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/reykjavik/reyk-main.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/reykjavik/reyk-main.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Interesting findings:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A block of opcode:
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;beginning from &lt;code&gt;0x4520&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;spanning for &lt;code&gt;0xf8&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;is passed to &lt;code&gt;enc&lt;/code&gt; function. The destination of the result is set for &lt;code&gt;#0x2400&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Whitehorse</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-whitehorse/</link><pubDate>Tue, 01 Sep 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-whitehorse/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/whitehorse/whitehorse.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/whitehorse/whitehorse.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Slaps you with a manual:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/whitehorse/whitehorse-details.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/whitehorse/whitehorse-details.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;This lock is &lt;strong&gt;attached to a HSM-2 module&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Function to unlock door &lt;strong&gt;no longer in the lock firmware&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; function just calls &lt;code&gt;login&lt;/code&gt;. You set a breakpoint at &lt;code&gt;login&lt;/code&gt; and a quick test input of &lt;code&gt;aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/whitehorse/whitehorse-first-test-input.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/whitehorse/whitehorse-first-test-input.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;login&lt;/code&gt; function:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/whitehorse/whitehorse-login.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/whitehorse/whitehorse-login.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The prompt gives a range for input to be between 8 to 16 characters.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;However, the parameters for the &lt;code&gt;getsn&lt;/code&gt; function:
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;r14&lt;/code&gt;: Holds the length of the input buffer. &lt;code&gt;#0x30(48)&lt;/code&gt; characters. This is room for inputs &amp;gt; 16 chars.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;r15&lt;/code&gt;: Holds the address to the input buffer -&amp;gt; &lt;code&gt;#0x34d2&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Input is passed to &lt;code&gt;conditional_unlock_door&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/whitehorse/whitehorse-conditional.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/whitehorse/whitehorse-conditional.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Cusco</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-cusco/</link><pubDate>Wed, 26 Aug 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-cusco/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cusco/cusco.jpg"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cusco/cusco.jpg"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cusco/cusco-details.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cusco/cusco-details.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this manual, you notice that:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;This lock is attached to &lt;strong&gt;HSM-1&lt;/strong&gt; module.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;conditional flag&lt;/strong&gt; that accidentally gets set when very long passwords are put in, has been &lt;strong&gt;removed&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cusco/cusco-test-inpput.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cusco/cusco-test-inpput.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After a &lt;em&gt;fast fail&lt;/em&gt; using a test input: &lt;code&gt;aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa&lt;/code&gt;, turns out the program does not exit. It instead, loops back to the start of the program.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cusco/cusco-loop-second-login.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/cusco/cusco-loop-second-login.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is interesting. Why? Because it is a &lt;strong&gt;clue&lt;/strong&gt; that at some point at the end of a failed password verification; instead of a program exit, the return address points to the beginning instruction to jump to. This shall become clear soon.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Hanoi</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-hanoi/</link><pubDate>Wed, 26 Aug 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-hanoi/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/hanoi/hanoi.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/hanoi/hanoi.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You get to Hanoi, you find a manual.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/hanoi/hanoi-details.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/hanoi/hanoi-details.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Things are a bit different this time:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;This Lock is attached to LockIT Pro &lt;strong&gt;HSM-1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Password &lt;strong&gt;stored in the HSM&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Password set by connecting to app through the HSM and restarting the Lock.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A flag is set&lt;/strong&gt; by the HSM after validating a correct password input.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; function just calls the &lt;code&gt;login&lt;/code&gt; function. The prompt for writing your test input gives an interesting clue: the password range.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: New Orleans</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-new-orleans/</link><pubDate>Wed, 26 Aug 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-new-orleans/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/New-Orleans.jpg"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/New-Orleans.jpg"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You find a manual for the LockIT Pro Lock:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/New-Orleans-details.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/New-Orleans-details.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You learn some things from the manual:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;It is &lt;strong&gt;not attached&lt;/strong&gt; to a HSM module.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Password set by entering it on the app restarting the lock.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You are presented with a live debugger, a live memory dump, a disassembler and a view of the register states.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Looking through the main you notice a &lt;code&gt;create_password&lt;/code&gt; function that gets called before the input is required or a check for correct input is done.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>MicroCorruption: Sydney</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-sydney/</link><pubDate>Wed, 26 Aug 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/microcorruption-sydney/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/sydney/sydney.jpg"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/sydney/sydney.jpg"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Another LockIT Pro Lock manual but this is a more secure, revised version they say ;) :&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/sydney/sydney-details.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/sydney/sydney-details.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You learn that:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The lock is &lt;strong&gt;not attached to a HSM&lt;/strong&gt;(Hardware Security Module).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The password is now &lt;strong&gt;not stored&lt;/strong&gt; in memory.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is how the &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; function looks like:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/sydney/sydney-check.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/microcorruption/sydney/sydney-check.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is a &lt;code&gt;check_password&lt;/code&gt; function called. You do the usual quick run of the program using a dummy input &lt;code&gt;test&lt;/code&gt;, set a breakpoint on &lt;code&gt;check_password&lt;/code&gt; and follow through the flow.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>AH19CTF WriteUps: Command Parser</title><link>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/commandparser/</link><pubDate>Sat, 17 Aug 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>http://evalevanto.github.io/posts/commandparser/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/commandparser.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/commandparser.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 id="whats-provided"&gt;What&amp;rsquo;s provided:&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Server access to a directory containing an executable and a flag file.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/server_view.png"&gt;&lt;img class="img" src="http://evalevanto.github.io/images/server_view.png"
 alt/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You cannot just &lt;code&gt;cat flag&lt;/code&gt; because &lt;code&gt;r--r----- 1 commandparserctf-pwn root ... flag&lt;/code&gt;
and of course, your &lt;code&gt;whoami&lt;/code&gt; profile is not in the sudoers list.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A link to download the executable file.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is good. You can dissassemble it later.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;h4 id="lets-get-cracking-d"&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s get cracking :D&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Your first step is to run the executable and have a clue of what it does. Notice the file permissions on the commandparser file above &lt;code&gt;-rwsr-xr-x&lt;/code&gt;: the setuid flag &lt;code&gt;s&lt;/code&gt;. This means that the file runs with escalated priviledge, in this case, the root(owner of the file). The program asks for an input that is a command to execute. You put in &lt;code&gt;/bin/cat flag&lt;/code&gt;; perhaps being run in UID root, this might spit back the flag. You get a &lt;code&gt;input not allowed&lt;/code&gt; error instead and the program exits.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>